{"title_page": "House of Castellane", "text_new": "{{See also|Castellane}}\n{{Infobox Family\n| colour            = \n| name              = House of Castellane\n| image             = \n| crest             = Blason Maison de Castellane.png\n| caption           = \n| ethnicity         = \n| region            = [[Provence]]\n| early_forms       = \n| origin            = \n| members           = \n| otherfamilies     = [[House of Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord|Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord]]<br>[[Duke of Noailles|Noailles]]<br>[[Jay Gould|Gould]]\n| distinctions      = \n| traditions        = \n| heirlooms         =\n| estate            = [[Ch\u00e2teau de Rochecotte]]<br>[[Nesvizh Castle]]\n| meaning           = \n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\nThe '''House of Castellane''' is a very ancient [[French nobility|French noble house]] originating in [[Provence]] and descended from Thibault, count of Arles in the 9th century.\n\n==History==\nBoniface, 1st sovereign baron<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?pg=PA321&lpg=PA321&dq=baron+de+Castellane+,+comme+souverain+ind%C3%A9pendant&sig=ACfU3U3JplJUKAJgmLDXy3ybyToTqdoW1w&id=rGI_AQAAMAAJ&ots=sqzxUrQcTr&output=text|title=Annuaire de la noblesse de France|date=1894|publisher=Au Bureau de la publication|language=fr}}</ref> de Castellane, lived in the 11th century. The sovereign barons de Castellane ruled over a small state<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?pg=PA321&lpg=PA321&dq=baron+de+Castellane+,+comme+souverain+ind%C3%A9pendant&sig=ACfU3U3JplJUKAJgmLDXy3ybyToTqdoW1w&id=rGI_AQAAMAAJ&ots=sqzxUrQcTr&output=text|title=Annuaire de la noblesse de France|date=1894|publisher=Au Bureau de la publication|language=fr}}</ref> bordering the [[Haute-Provence]] until the beginning of the 13th century, rendering homage to their overlord the [[count of Provence]].\n\nEven after this they retained de jure sovereignty: \"\n\n\"Even after having been forced to pay homage to the Counts of Provence, these powerful feudal lords retained the fullness of the authority they exercised over their vassals.\"\n\nAccording to Lumens (Histoire de Castellane, published by J.-B. Shares...[t]he town, the castle and the rock of Castellane and declared him sovereign after the example of his elders;\n\nIn 1993, king [[Juan Carlos I of Spain|Juan Carlos I]] rehabilitated the title of [[Duke of Almaz\u00e1n de Saint Priest]] on a descendant of the first duke, Louis Provence Boniface de Castellane (1912\u20131996), who became the 2nd Duke de Almaz\u00e1n de Saint Priest, with his daughter B\u00e9atrice Marguerite Marie-Th\u00e9r\u00e8se de Castellane (b. 1944) following him as 3rd Duchess de Almaz\u00e1n de Saint Priest.\n\n==Family tree==\n{{Tree list}}\n*'''''Boniface'' Louis Andr\u00e9 de Castellane''' (1758\u20131837) \u221e Ad\u00e9la\u00efde Louise Guyonne de Rohan-Chabot\n**'''[[Boniface de Castellane (1788-1862)|Esprit Victor Elisabeth ''Boniface'' de Castellane]]''' (1788\u20131862)<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=Decease of an Old French Soldier|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1862/10/11/news/interesting-paris-imperial-manifesto-roman-question-various-interpretations-it.html |quote=One of the most eccentric military notabilities of the present epoch, the Marshal Count Castellane, has just died at Lyons. |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 11, 1862 |accessdate=2015-01-03 }}</ref>, [[List of Marshals of France|mar\u00e9chal de France]] \u221e (1813) Louise ''Cord\u00e9lia'' Eucharis Greffulhe (1796\u20131847)\n*** '''[[Henri de Castellane]]''' (1814\u20131847) \u221e (1839) [[Pauline de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord|Jos\u00e9phine ''Pauline'' de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord]] (1820\u20131890)\n**** [[Marie de Castellane|''Marie'' Doroth\u00e9e \u00c9lisabeth de Castellane]] (1840\u20131915) \u221e (1857) Prince Antoine Radziwill (1833\u20131904)\n**** '''[[Antoine de Castellane]]''' (1844\u20131917) \u221e (1866) Anne Marie Le Clerc de Juign\u00e9 (1847\u20131934)\n***** '''[[Boniface de Castellane (1867-1932)|Boniface de Castellane]]''' (1867-1932) \u221e (1895) [[Anna Gould]] (1875\u20131961)\n****** '''Boniface de Castellane''' (1896-1946) \u221e Yvonne Patenotre\n******* Raymonde de Castellane (1921\u20132006) \u221e Robert Bertin\n******* Pauline de Castellane (born 1923) \u221e Charles Jehannot d'Huriel de Bartillat (1910\u20131977), had issue\n*******{{Tree list/final branch}} Elisabeth de Castellane (1928\u20131991) \u221e Jean de Caumont La Force (1920\u20131986)\n****** [[Georges de Castellane]] (1897\u20131944) \u221e Florinda Fern\u00e1ndez Anchorena (born 1901)\n*******{{Tree list/final branch}} Diane de Castellane \u221e [[Philippe Fran\u00e7ois Armand Marie de Noailles|Philippe de Noailles, duc de Mouchy]]\n****** Jay de Castellane (1902\u20131956)\n***** [[Jean de Castellane]] (1868\u20131965) \u221e (1898) [[Doroth\u00e9e de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord]] (1862\u20131948)\n*****{{Tree list/final branch}} [[Stanislas de Castellane]] (1876\u20131959) \u221e (1901) Natalia Terry y Sanchez (1877-1962) (sister of [[Emilio Terry]])\n****** Henri de Castellane (1903\u20131937)\n****** {{Tree list/final branch}} Fran\u00e7ois de Castellane (1908\u20131988)\n*** [[Sophie de Castellane]] (1818\u20131904) \u221e (1) (1836) Marquis de Contades \u221e (2) (1859) Comte de Baulaincourt\n*** Rachel Elisabeth ''Pauline'' de Castellane (1823\u20131895) \u221e (1) (1844) Maximilien de Hatzfeld (1813\u20131859) \u221e (2) (1861) Napol\u00e9on-''Louis'' de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord (1811\u20131898), duc de Dino et de Talleyrand\n****{{Tree list/final branch}} [[Doroth\u00e9e de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord|Doroth\u00e9e (''\"Dolly\"'') de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord]] (1862\u20131948) \u221e (1881) [[Charles Egon IV, Prince of F\u00fcrstenberg]] (1852\u20131896) \u221e (1898) [[Jean de Castellane]] (1868\u20131965)\n***{{Tree list/final branch}} Pierre de Castellane (1824\u20131883)\n{{Tree list/end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{commons}}\n*[[House of Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:House of Castellane| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|Castellane}}\n{{Infobox Family\n| colour            = \n| name              = House of Castellane\n| image             = \n| crest             = Blason Maison de Castellane.png\n| caption           = \n| ethnicity         = \n| region            = [[Provence]]\n| early_forms       = \n| origin            = \n| members           = \n| otherfamilies     = [[House of Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord|Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord]]<br>[[Duke of Noailles|Noailles]]<br>[[Jay Gould|Gould]]\n| distinctions      = \n| traditions        = \n| heirlooms         =\n| estate            = [[Ch\u00e2teau de Rochecotte]]<br>[[Nesvizh Castle]]\n| meaning           = \n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\nThe '''House of Castellane''' is a very ancient [[French nobility|French noble house]] originating in [[Provence]] and descended from Thibault, count of Arles in the 9th century.\n\n==History==\nBoniface, 1st sovereign baron<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?pg=PA321&lpg=PA321&dq=baron+de+Castellane+,+comme+souverain+ind%C3%A9pendant&sig=ACfU3U3JplJUKAJgmLDXy3ybyToTqdoW1w&id=rGI_AQAAMAAJ&ots=sqzxUrQcTr&output=text|title=Annuaire de la noblesse de France|date=1894|publisher=Au Bureau de la publication|language=fr}}</ref> de Castellane, lived in the 11th century. The sovereign barons de Castellane ruled over a small state<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?pg=PA321&lpg=PA321&dq=baron+de+Castellane+,+comme+souverain+ind%C3%A9pendant&sig=ACfU3U3JplJUKAJgmLDXy3ybyToTqdoW1w&id=rGI_AQAAMAAJ&ots=sqzxUrQcTr&output=text|title=Annuaire de la noblesse de France|date=1894|publisher=Au Bureau de la publication|language=fr}}</ref> bordering the [[Haute-Provence]] until the beginning of the 13th century, rendering homage to their overlord the [[count of Provence]].\n\nEven after this they retained de jure sovereignty: \"\n\n\n\"Even after having been forced to pay homage to the Counts of Provence, these powerful feudal lords retained the fullness of the authority they exercised over their vassals.\"\n\nAccording to Lumens (Histoire de Castellane, published by J.-B. Shares...[t]he town, the castle and the rock of Castellane and declared him sovereign after the example of his elders;\n\n\n\n\n\nIn 1993, king [[Juan Carlos I of Spain|Juan Carlos I]] rehabilitated the title of [[Duke of Almaz\u00e1n de Saint Priest]] on a descendant of the first duke, Louis Provence Boniface de Castellane (1912\u20131996), who became the 2nd Duke de Almaz\u00e1n de Saint Priest, with his daughter B\u00e9atrice Marguerite Marie-Th\u00e9r\u00e8se de Castellane (b. 1944) following him as 3rd Duchess de Almaz\u00e1n de Saint Priest.\n\n==Family tree==\n{{Tree list}}\n*'''''Boniface'' Louis Andr\u00e9 de Castellane''' (1758\u20131837) \u221e Ad\u00e9la\u00efde Louise Guyonne de Rohan-Chabot\n**'''[[Boniface de Castellane (1788-1862)|Esprit Victor Elisabeth ''Boniface'' de Castellane]]''' (1788\u20131862)<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=Decease of an Old French Soldier|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1862/10/11/news/interesting-paris-imperial-manifesto-roman-question-various-interpretations-it.html |quote=One of the most eccentric military notabilities of the present epoch, the Marshal Count Castellane, has just died at Lyons. |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 11, 1862 |accessdate=2015-01-03 }}</ref>, [[List of Marshals of France|mar\u00e9chal de France]] \u221e (1813) Louise ''Cord\u00e9lia'' Eucharis Greffulhe (1796\u20131847)\n*** '''[[Henri de Castellane]]''' (1814\u20131847) \u221e (1839) [[Pauline de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord|Jos\u00e9phine ''Pauline'' de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord]] (1820\u20131890)\n**** [[Marie de Castellane|''Marie'' Doroth\u00e9e \u00c9lisabeth de Castellane]] (1840\u20131915) \u221e (1857) Prince Antoine Radziwill (1833\u20131904)\n**** '''[[Antoine de Castellane]]''' (1844\u20131917) \u221e (1866) Anne Marie Le Clerc de Juig