{"title_page": "Sne\u017eana", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=June 2012}}\n\n'''Sne\u017eana''' ([[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]]: \u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430), also transliterated '''Snezhana''', is a [[Slavic names|Slavic]], [[Circassians|Circassian]], and [[Lithuanians|Lithuanian]] feminine given name, possibly derived from ''sneg'' (\"snow\") and ''\u017eena'' (\"woman\"). It is popular in [[former Yugoslavia]], [[Russia]] and [[Bulgaria]]. Other spellings include ''Snje\u017eana'' and ''Snije\u017eana'', found in Croatia and Serbs outside Serbia. Sne\u017eana was the fifth most popular name in the [[Republic of Macedonia]] in 2011.<ref>[http://www.stat.gov.mk/Publikacii/Mak_Brojki_2012_A.pdf Macedonia in Figures, 2012, page 16]</ref> In the decade from 1960 to 1970 Sne\u017eana was the most popular name in Serbia.<ref>[http://www.znacenje-imena.com/najpopularnija_srpska_imena_1960_1970 Znacenje Imena- Meaning of the Names] </ref> Based on research conducted on 31 December 2007 by the [[Statistical Office of Slovenia]], Sne\u017eana and Sergei were the 198th most common personal names in [[Slovenia]]. ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430'' (Snezhana) and ''\u0421\u0438\u043d\u044d\u0436\u0430\u043d'' (Sinejan), literally meaning \"My sharp-eyed [girl]\" in Circassian language, are one of the most common traditional Circassian female names. A derivative ''\u041d\u044d\u0436\u0430\u043d'' (Nejan) is also popular amongst Circassian girls, though it can also be used as a male name, since it does not have the -a suffix. ''Sne\u017ean'', ''Snje\u017ean'', ''Sne\u017eko'', and ''Snje\u017eko'' are some other male forms mainly in Christian former Yugoslavians. ''Sne\u017eko'' is a common surname in Lithuania. [[Sn\u011b\u017eka]] is also the name of a mountain on the border between the [[Czech Republic]] and [[Poland]]. In Russia, there is a women's football club \"\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430\" based in [[Lyubertsy]], [[Moscow Oblast]].\n\n==Variations==\n{| width=1000\n|  valign=top width=50% | \n<br />'''Female forms''': \n<br />''\u0421\u043d\u0456\u0436\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0456\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430'', ([[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]])\n<br />''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u0301\u043d\u0430'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u0301\u043d\u043d\u0430'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u043e\u043a'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u0301\u043d\u043e\u0447\u043a\u0430'' ([[Russian given name#Diminutive forms|diminutive]]), ([[Russian language|Russian]])\n<br />''Sne\u017eana'', ''Sne\u017ea'', ([[Slovenian language|Slovenian]])\n<br />''Sne\u017eana'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430'', ([[Serbian language|Serbian]] and [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]])\n<br />''Snje\u017eana'', ''Snije\u017eana'', ([[Croatian language|Croatian]])\n<br />''\u0421\u0438\u043d\u044d\u0436\u0430\u043d'', ''Sinejan'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430'', ''\u041d\u044d\u0436\u0430\u043d'', ''Nejan'', ([[Circassian language|Circassian]])\n<br />''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430'', ([[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]])\n<br />''Sne\u017ea'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430'', ''Sne\u017eanka'', ''Sne\u017eica'', ''Sne\u017eka'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u043a\u0430'', ''Sne\u017ena''\n<br />''\u0416\u0430\u043d\u0430'', ''Zhana'', ''\u017dana'', ''\u0416\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430'', ''Zhanna'', ''\u017danna''\n\n|  valign=top width=50% |\n<br />'''Male forms''': \n<br />''Sne\u017ean'', ''Sne\u017eko''\n<br />''Snje\u017ean'', ''Snje\u017eko''\n<br />''Sinejan'', ''Nejan'', ''Jan''\n|}\n\n==Notable people named Sne\u017eana==\n*[[Sne\u017eana Rodi\u010d]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Pajki\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Aleksi\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Bogdanovi\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Hrepevnik]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Panti\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Babi\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Malovi\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Samard\u017ei\u0107-Markovi\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Prorok]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Nik\u0161i\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Zori\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Male\u0161evi\u010d]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Slavic names]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Snezana}}\n[[Category:Bulgarian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Circassian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Croatian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Macedonian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Russian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Serbian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Slavic feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Slovene feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian feminine given names]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=June 2012}}\n\n'''Sne\u017eana''' ([[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]]: \u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430), also transliterated '''Snezhana''', is a [[Slavic names|Slavic]], [[Circassians|Circassian]], and [[Lithuanians|Lithuanian]] feminine given name, possibly derived from ''sneg'' (\"snow\") and ''\u017eena'' (\"woman\"). It is popular in [[former Yugoslavia]], [[Russia]] and [[Bulgaria]]. Other spellings include ''Snje\u017eana'' and ''Snije\u017eana'', found in Croatia and Serbs outside Serbia. Sne\u017eana was the fifth most popular name in the [[Republic of Macedonia]] in 2011.<ref>[http://www.stat.gov.mk/Publikacii/Mak_Brojki_2012_A.pdf Macedonia in Figures, 2012, page 16]</ref> In the decade from 1960 to 1970 Sne\u017eana was the most popular name in Serbia.<ref>[http://www.znacenje-imena.com/najpopularnija_srpska_imena_1960_1970 Znacenje Imena- Meaning of the Names] </ref> Based on research conducted on 31 December 2007 by the [[Statistical Office of Slovenia]], Sne\u017eana and Sergei were the 198th most common personal names in [[Slovenia]]. ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430'' (Snezhana) and ''\u0421\u0438\u043d\u044d\u0436\u0430\u043d'' (Sinejan), literally meaning \"My sharp-eyed [girl]\" in Circassian language, are one of the most common traditional Circassian female names. A derivative ''\u041d\u044d\u0436\u0430\u043d'' (Nejan) is also popular amongst Circassian girls, though it can also be used as a male name, since it does not have the -a suffix. ''Sne\u017ean'', ''Snje\u017ean'', ''Sne\u017eko'', and ''Snje\u017eko'' are some other male forms mainly in Christian former Yugoslavians. ''Sne\u017eko'' is a common surname in Lithuania. [[Sn\u011b\u017eka]] is also the name of a mountain a mountain on the border between the [[Czech Republic]] and [[Poland]]. In Russia, there is a women's football club \"\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430\" based in [[Lyubertsy]], [[Moscow Oblast]].\n\n==Variations==\n{| width=1000\n|  valign=top width=50% | \n<br />'''Female forms''': \n<br />''\u0421\u043d\u0456\u0436\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0456\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430'', ([[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]])\n<br />''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u0301\u043d\u0430'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u0301\u043d\u043d\u0430'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u043e\u043a'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u0301\u043d\u043e\u0447\u043a\u0430'' ([[Russian given name#Diminutive forms|diminutive]]), ([[Russian language|Russian]])\n<br />''Sne\u017eana'', ''Sne\u017ea'', ([[Slovenian language|Slovenian]])\n<br />''Sne\u017eana'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430'', ([[Serbian language|Serbian]] and [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]])\n<br />''Snje\u017eana'', ''Snije\u017eana'', ([[Croatian language|Croatian]])\n<br />''\u0421\u0438\u043d\u044d\u0436\u0430\u043d'', ''Sinejan'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430'', ''\u041d\u044d\u0436\u0430\u043d'', ''Nejan'', ([[Circassian language|Circassian]])\n<br />''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430'', ([[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]])\n<br />''Sne\u017ea'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u0430'', ''Sne\u017eanka'', ''Sne\u017eica'', ''Sne\u017eka'', ''\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u043a\u0430'', ''Sne\u017ena''\n<br />''\u0416\u0430\u043d\u0430'', ''Zhana'', ''\u017dana'', ''\u0416\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430'', ''Zhanna'', ''\u017danna''\n\n|  valign=top width=50% |\n<br />'''Male forms''': \n<br />''Sne\u017ean'', ''Sne\u017eko''\n<br />''Snje\u017ean'', ''Snje\u017eko''\n<br />''Sinejan'', ''Nejan'', ''Jan''\n|}\n\n==Notable people named Sne\u017eana==\n*[[Sne\u017eana Rodi\u010d]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Pajki\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Aleksi\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Bogdanovi\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Hrepevnik]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Panti\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Babi\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Malovi\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Samard\u017ei\u0107-Markovi\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Prorok]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Nik\u0161i\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Zori\u0107]]\n*[[Sne\u017eana Male\u0161evi\u010d]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Slavic names]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Snezana}}\n[[Category:Bulgarian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Circassian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Croatian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Macedonian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Russian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Serbian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Slavic feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Slovene feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian feminine given names]]\n", "name_user": "Ak-hannibal", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sne%C5%BEana"}
{"title_page": "Alberta Health Services", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| name = Alberta Health Services\n| type = Health care\n| seal = \n| logo = File:Alberta Health Services Logo.svg\n| formed = {{Start date and age|2009|04|01}}\n| preceding1 = Aspen Health Region\n| preceding2 = Calgary Health Region\n| jurisdiction = [[Government of Alberta]]\n| headquarters = [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]]\n| motto = Healthy Albertans. Healthy Communities. Together.\n| employees = 109,000 (2017)<ref name=\"16-17\">{{cite web|title=Alberta Health Services 2016-17 Annual Report|url=https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/assets/about/publications/ahs-pub-2016-2017-annual-report.pdf|website=Alberta Health Services|publisher=Alberta Health Services|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107005418/https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/assets/about/publications/ahs-pub-2016-2017-annual-report.pdf|archivedate=January 6, 2018|language=English|accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n| budget = $21.4 billion (2017)<ref name=\"Budget\">{{cite web|title=Health funding forecast: 2017 Q2 Update|url=http://www.health.alberta.ca/about/health-funding.html|website=Health Alberta|publisher=Government of Alberta|accessdate=January 6, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107005335/http://www.health.alberta.ca/about/health-funding.html|archivedate=January 6, 2018|language=English|date=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n| minister1_name = [[Tyler Shandro]]\n| minister1_pfo = Minister of Health\n| minister2_name = \n| minister2_pfo = \n| deputyminister1_name = \n| deputyminister1_pfo = \n| deputyminister2_name = \n| deputyminister2_pfo = \n| chief1_name = \n| chief1_position = \n| chief2_name = \n| chief2_position = \n| chief3_name = \n| chief3_position = \n| chief4_name = \n| chief4_position = \n| chief5_name = \n| chief5_position = \n| chief6_name = \n| public_protector = \n| deputy = \n| chief6_position = \n| chief7_name = \n| chief7_position = \n| chief8_name = \n| chief8_position = \n| chief9_name = \n| chief9_position = \n| parent_department = [[Government of Alberta]]\n| parent_agency = Alberta Health<ref name=\"ABH\">{{cite web|title=Alberta Health|url=http://www.health.alberta.ca/|website=Health Alberta|publisher=Government of Alberta|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107005556/http://www.health.alberta.ca/|archivedate=January 6, 2018|language=English|accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|https://albertahealthservices.ca}}\n| agency_id = \n}}\n'''Alberta Health Services''' ('''AHS''') is the single [[Health regions of Canada|health authority]] for the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian province]] of [[Alberta]].\n\nAlberta Health Services delivers medical care on behalf of the [[Government of Alberta]]'s Ministry of Health<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.health.alberta.ca/|website=Alberta Health|title=Alberta Health|publisher=Government of Alberta|access-date=January 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107073622/http://www.health.alberta.ca/|archive-date=January 7, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> through 400 facilities throughout the province, including hospitals, clinics, continuing care facilities, mental health facilities and community health sites, while providing a variety of programs and services.\n\nAHS is the largest single health authority in Canada and is the largest employer in the province of Alberta as well as being the fifth largest single employer in Canada.\n\nAlberta Health Services is headquartered in [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]].\n\n==Overview==\nAccording to the December 31, 2019 [[Ernst & Young]] review of AHS performance commissioned by Alberta Health, Alberta has Canada's \"largest integrated provincial health care system\". AHS served 4.3 Albertan and had a staff of 125,000 staff and 10,000 physicians.<ref name=\"EY_AHS_20191231\">{{Cite report| title = Alberta Health Services Performance Review Summary Report |date=December 31, 2019| access-date = April 5, 2020| url = https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/c0724ccd-832e-41bc-90d6-a0cd16bc6954/resource/1e03ea8a-7948-48c4-bca4-109c20ce0f02/download/health-ahs-review-summary-report.pdf |format=PDF |work=[[Ernst & Young]] |pages=101}}</ref>{{rp|3}} Ernst & Young said that AHS was \"one of Canada's top 100 employers.\" AHS foundations raise over $250 million annually.<ref name=\"EY_AHS_20191231\"/>{{rp|3}}\n\n==History==\nThe Alberta Health Services, which was established in May 15, 2008, as a quasi-independent agency of the Alberta government to public health services throughout the province. \n\n[[Ed Stelmach]], who served as Alberta's premier from December 2006 to October 2011, as leader of the [[Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta]], introduced major reforms to Alberta's health-care system. On May 15, 2008, Health Minister [[Ron Liepert]] announced that as of April 1, 2009, one provincial governance board\u2014the Alberta Health Services Board\u2014would consolidate the \"$13-billion-a-year system into one public corporation\", replacing Alberta's nine regional health authority boards\u2014 Aspen Health Region, Calgary Health Region, Capital Health Region, Chinook Health Region, David Thompson Health Region, East Central Health Region, Northern Lights Health Region, Palliser Health Region, and Peace Country Health Region.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Markusoff_20080515\">{{cite news|url=http://www.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/story.html?id=4b0743f0-2046-4b13-8be7-7e2e4ca7e10d |title=Tories create health superboard: Stelmach plan will see single body rule nine regions |first1=Jason |last1=Markusoff |first2=Archie |last2=McLean |access-date=June 12, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090509222347/http://www2.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/story.html?id=4b0743f0-2046-4b13-8be7-7e2e4ca7e10d |archivedate=May 9, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2009, the Health Governance Transition Amendment Act dissolved the Alberta Mental Health Board, the Alberta Cancer Board and the Alberta Alcohol and Drug Abuse Commission,<ref name=\"Liepert_2009\">{{cite report |last=Liepert |first=RON |date=2009 |title=Provincial health structure: Alberta |series=Health Innovation Report|url=http://www.healthinnovationforum.org/2009/nov/01/recent-changes-health-structures-alberta/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124083008/http://www.healthinnovationforum.org/2009/nov/01/recent-changes-health-structures-alberta/ |archivedate=January 24, 2010 |access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|12\u20133}}<ref>{{citation |last=Philippon |first= D. |date=2009 |title=Health care system reorganization: expectations, approaches and impact |series=Health Innovation Report}}</ref>{{rp|44\u201349}} and completed the transition to Alberta Health Services (AHS).<ref name=\"AHS_history_2018\">{{cite web|title=Who We Are |url=https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/about/about.aspx|website=Alberta Health Services|publisher=Alberta Health Services|accessdate=January 6, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107010616/https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/about/about.aspx|archivedate=January 6, 2018|language=English}}</ref>\n\nPrior to these changes, health services in Alberta had undergone several governance reorganization which had resulted in fewer separate public organizational entities, in 1996,<ref>Philippon, D. J. and S. A. Wasylyshyn (1996). Health-care reform in Alberta. ''Canadian Public Administration'' 39(1): 70-84.</ref><ref>Reay, T. and C. R. Hinings (2005). The Recomposition of an Organizational Field: Health Care in Alberta. ''Organization Studies'' 26(3): 351-384.</ref> 2003,<ref>Hinings, C. R., A. Casebeer, et al. (2003). Regionalizing Healthcare in Alberta: Legislated Change, Uncertainty and Loose Coupling ''[[British Journal of Management]]'' 14:S1(December): S15-S30.</ref> and 2006.<ref>Casebeer, A., T. Reay, et al. (2006). Experiences of Regionalization: Assessing Multiple Stakeholder Perspectives across Time. ''Healthcare Quarterly'' 9(2): 32-43.</ref>\n\n==Mission and organization==\nAHS provides health services to some patients in British Columbia, Saskatchewan, and the Northwest Territories, as well as to over 4.3 million Albertans.<ref name=\"EY_AHS_20191231\"/>{{rp|3}} \n\nAlberta Health Services has articulated three broad goals (access, quality and sustainability) which expand into eight 'areas of focus' (e.g. improving access, fit for the future, learning and improving) and 20 strategic priorities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/files/org-strategic-direction.pdf |title=strategic direction |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |date= |accessdate=January 7, 2018 }}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAlberta Health Services has been organized so as to separate acute hospital facilities (with separate reporting lines for major tertiary, metropolitan and regional hospitals) from smaller hospitals and community services, the latter of which are organized into five zones (North, Edmonton, Central, Calgary and South).  The Calgary Zone, for example, includes some sites and services formerly administered by the [[Calgary Health Region]] while other services have been reorganized on a provincial scale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/files/org-orgchart.pdf |title=formal structure |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007191554/http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/files/org-orgchart.pdf |archive-date=October 7, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nThe organization was initially overseen by a board of directors, followed by an official administrator, and most recently, again by a board of directors. The Alberta Health Services Board reports to the Minister of Health.<ref name=\"EY_AHS_20191231\"/>{{rp|3}} \n\n[[Stephen Duckett]] was the inaugural president and chief executive officer of the newly created health \"superboard\", Alberta Health Services, and served from the spring of 2009 until November 2010, when then-provincial Health Minister [[Gene Zwozdesky]] asked him to resign.<ref name=\"CBC_20201224\">{{Cite news| date = November 24, 2010| title = Alberta health board replaces controversial CEO|work= CBC News| access-date = April 5, 2020| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-health-board-replaces-controversial-ceo-1.886067}}</ref> Significant budget cuts\u2014of about CA $1 billion\u2014were imposed on AHS by Premier Stelmach, soon after Duckett's appointment.<ref name=\"CBC_20090828\">{{Cite news| date = August 28, 2009| title = Health-care buyouts spark interest, raise concerns |work=CBC News| access-date = April 5, 2020| date = 2009-08-28| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/health-care-buyouts-spark-interest-raise-concerns-1.826258}}</ref> \n\nChris Eagle served as AHS CEO from November 23, 2010 until October 17, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/9226.asp |title=\"Dr. Chris Eagle steps down as AHS CEO\" |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031222854/http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/9226.asp |archive-date=October 31, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  \n\nOn June 12, 2013, Minister of Health [[Fred Horne]] fired the entire AHS Board over its refusal to cancel executive bonuses.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/alberta-health-minister-fires-board-over-executive-bonuses/article12490983/ |title=\"Alberta Health Minister fires entire board over executive bonuses\" |access-date=August 23, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814214121/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/alberta-health-minister-fires-board-over-executive-bonuses/article12490983/ |archive-date=August 14, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Three days later, Janet Davidson<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.health.alberta.ca/documents/NewBG-2013-06-15-AHS-Admin.pdf |title=\"Appointment details, AHS Administrator Janet M. Davidson\" |access-date=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011214023/http://www.health.alberta.ca/documents/NewBG-2013-06-15-AHS-Admin.pdf |archive-date=October 11, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> was appointed the AHS official administrator by Minister Horne to act in place of its board of directors. On September 12, 2013, John W. F. Cowell replaced Davidson as the official administrator.<ref>{{cite web |author=Government of Alberta |url=http://alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=34957BA1F0D67-C2F5-6A9F-C3AA752F708F46D0 |title=\"Statement from Health Minister Fred Horne on the appointment of Dr. Cowell\" |publisher=Alberta.ca |date=September 12, 2013 |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104223119/http://alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=34957BA1F0D67-C2F5-6A9F-C3AA752F708F46D0 |archive-date=January 4, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> AHS has subsequently had Carl Amrhein and David Carpenter as official administrators.\n\nVickie Kaminski served from May 2014 until her<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/vickie-kaminski-resigns-as-ceo-of-alberta-health-services-1.3340201 |title=\"Vickie Kaminski resigns as CEO of Alberta Health Services\" |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=November 27, 2015 |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008041325/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/vickie-kaminski-resigns-as-ceo-of-alberta-health-services-1.3340201 |archive-date=October 8, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> resignation in late 2015. \n\nThe Alberta Health Services Board has been re-introduced, effective November 27, 2015 with Linda Hughes appointed as the board chair.<ref>{{cite web |author=Government of Alberta |url=https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=38722D3908842-FE39-E61E-98C591CBE1D023C4 |title=\"New Alberta Health Services Board features strong health care expertise\" |publisher=Alberta.ca |date=October 23, 2015 |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107174935/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=38722D3908842-FE39-E61E-98C591CBE1D023C4 |archive-date=January 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn June 3, 2016, Verna Yiu became CEO.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/about/Page11898.aspx |title=AHS Executive Leadership Team &#124; Dr. Verna Yiu |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |date=June 3, 2016 |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108120446/https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/about/Page11898.aspx |archive-date=January 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, David Weyant, QC served as Board Chair, Brenda Hemmelgarn as Vice-Chair, and Brian Vaasjo, David Carpenter, Glenda Yeates, Heidi Overguard, Hugh D. Sommerville, Richard Dicerni, and [[Stephen Mandel]], serve as board members.<ref name=\"AHS_2020\">{{Cite web| title = Board Members| work = Alberta Health Services|date=2020| access-date = April 5, 2020| url = https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/about/Page12891.aspx}}</ref>\n\n==Employees==\nBy 2018, Alberta Health Services employs over 108,000 staff and more than 7,700 physicians,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/about/about.aspx |title=About AHS &#124; Alberta Health Services |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107010616/https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/about/about.aspx |archive-date=January 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> including clinical, administrative and support personnel across the province. Staff belong to a variety of professional organizations and associations, including [[United Nurses of Alberta]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.una.ab.ca/about |title=UNA \"about\" page |publisher=Una.ab.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108062413/https://www.una.ab.ca/about |archive-date=January 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> several locals of the [[Alberta Union of Provincial Employees]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aupe.org/about/ |title=AUPE \"about\" web page |publisher=Aupe.org |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108063342/https://www.aupe.org/about/ |archive-date=January 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the Health Sciences Association of Alberta.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hsaa.ca/about-HSAA |title=HSAA \"about\" page |access-date=January 4, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104204344/http://www.hsaa.ca/about-HSAA |archive-date=January 4, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n{{main|List of hospitals in Alberta}}\nBy 2010, AHS was maintaining and running a number of different types of facilities and services.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/facilities.asp |title=AHS facilities website |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201024752/http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/facilities.asp |archive-date=December 1, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> These included Cancer care for the prevention, detection, treatment, education and care of cancer patients, as well as to facilitate research of cancer; continuing and long-term care\nfor the treatment of patients with complex health needs requiring 24-hour on-site services from [[registered nurse]]s; emergency for immediate care of patients with all types of conditions; [[List of hospitals in Alberta|hospitals]] for medical, surgical, or psychiatric care of the sick and injured. There were also laboratories for the processing of medical samples and tests; mental health and addictions services for treatment and care of patients diagnosed with mental health or addiction issues and emergency medical services.\n\nAHS is directly responsible for both ground and air ambulance operations in the province, provided through a mix of both direct delivery and contracted providers.\n\nA wider array of miscellaneous health facilities include physiotherapy, occupational therapy, home care, hemodialysis and others, and also include Public Health Centres which provide services such as prenatal, postpartum, health promotion/disease and injury prevention, bereavement services, communicable disease and school health.  They also fund [[affordable housing]] for seniors at facilities, such as Silvera for Seniors.\n\nUrgent care services include treating patients with unexpected but not life-threatening issues requiring same day treatment.\n\nAHS also operates X-ray and imaging clinics for procedures such as [[MRI]]s, X-rays and other types of scans.\n\n===Laboratories===\n\nIn the early 1990s, most of Edmonton's hospital labs were privatized.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_20161004\">{{Cite web| title = Editorial: Alberta Health Services takeover of private lab services looks logical| work = Edmonton Journal|date=October 4, 2016| access-date = April 5, 2020| url = https://edmontonjournal.com/opinion/editorials/editorial-lab-transfer-looks-logical}}</ref>  The Edmonton regional health authority had a 15-year contract with the private company Dynalife, which was ending in the early 2010s.\n\nThe provincial government ordered regional health authorities to cut lab spending, which resulted in more public laboratories being established by 2005.\n\nBy 2006, all of the lab services in Calgary were under public control.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_20161004\"/>\n\nIn December 2013, Alberta Health Services proceeded with \"its plan to privatize all of its diagnostic lab services in Edmonton\".<ref name=\"CBC_20131211\">{{Cite news| date = December 11, 2013| title = Alberta Health Services privatizing Edmonton labs | work = CBC| access-date = April 4, 2020| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-health-services-privatizing-edmonton-labs-1.2460544}}</ref> AHS sent out request for proposals (RFP) for a \"private provider to establish a single $3 billion lab for the Edmonton Zone.\"<ref name=\"NCBI_Wright_20180726\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1177/2374289518785373| issn = 2374-2895| volume = 5| last = Wright| first = James R.| title = When Pathology and Laboratory Medicine Becomes a Commodity and Health Care Becomes Both Its Customer and Owner| journal = Academic Pathology| access-date = April 5, 2020| date = July 26, 2018| url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6073830/| pmid = 30083594| pmc = 6073830}}</ref>{{rp|2}}<ref name=\"CBC_20131211\"/> By October 16, 2014, Australia's Sonic Healthcare, a private company, had been selected.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Australia's Sonic Healthcare nets $3B contract for Edmonton labs |work= CBC News|date=October 16, 2014| accessdate = 2020-04-05| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/australia-s-sonichealthcare-nets-3b-contract-for-edmonton-labs-1.2802270}}</ref> They would have replaced \"hospital labs operated by AHS and Covenant Health, as well as the services now provided by the private company Dynalife.\" When the NDP won the [[2015 Alberta general election]], the contract with Sonic was cancelled.\n\nBy 2016, the largest medical testing facility in northern Alberta was the a central laboratory facility owned and operated by a private company in Edmonton, Dynalife.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Gerein_20200404\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta Health Services to take over Dynalife labs in 2022| work = Edmonton Journal|first=Keith |last=Gerein |date=October 1, 2016  | access-date = April 4, 2020| url = https://edmontonjournal.com/news/local-news/alberta-health-services-to-take-over-dynalife-labs-in-2022}}</ref> As of January 23, 2016, DynaLIFE Dx was owned by Toronto-headquartered LifeLabs and the [[Burlington, North Carolina]]-headquartered [[LabCorp]], or Laboratory Corporation of America Holdings, which operates one of the largest clinical laboratory networks in the world. LabCorp had acquired all outstanding shares of Canadian medical laboratory services company [[Dynacare|Dynacare Inc.]] for $480 million in May 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/dynacare-accepts-offer-from-labcorp/article1023077/|title=Dynacare accepts offer from LabCorp|last=|first=|date=2002-05-10|website=[[The Globe and Mail]]|publisher=Phillip Crawley|access-date=2016-10-14}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, Elisabeth Ballermann, then-President of the [[Health Sciences Association of Alberta]] (HSAA), which represented 1,600 lab workers in both the private and public sector, said that HSAA members had \"long wanted lab services delivered by the public system\". Ballerman said she was convinced, they could \"do high quality, world-class work in the public sector. She expressed concern\"that under the contract, the new facility to house the Edmonton lab would be owned by a private company, not by Albertans.\"<ref name=\"CBC_20150813\">{{Cite news| title = Health minister cancels $3B lab contract with Sonic Healthcare |work=CBC News| work = CBC| access-date = April 4, 2020| date = August 13, 2015| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/health-minister-cancels-3b-contract-will-not-expand-private-services-in-alberta-1.3190004}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, then-Premier [[Rachel Notley]], leader of the [[Alberta New Democratic Party]], announced that the [[Alberta New Democratic Party]] (NDP) government was beginning the process of taking over testing done by Dynacare as part of the NDP's campaign promises during the [[2015 Alberta general election]], to \"bring medical lab services under greater public control.\"<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Gerein_20200404\"/>\n\nThe newly-elected [[United Conservative Party]] (UCP) government's Health Minister [[Tyler Shandro]], cancelled the construction of a new super-lab\u2014a \"$595-million centralized public lab facility next to the University of Alberta\u2019s south campus\".<ref name=\"canhealth_20190626\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta's new government cancels superlab |work= Canadian Healthcare Technology| access-date = April 4, 2020 |date=June 26, 2019| url = https://www.canhealth.com/2019/06/26/albertas-new-government-cancels-superlab/}}</ref>  Shandro also exited the \"planned $50-million buyout of private lab services company Dynalife by 2022\", saying that he disagreed with the NDP's decision to \"nationalize Dynalife \u2013 to nationalize laboratory services in Alberta.\u201d<ref name=\"canhealth_20190626\"/>\n\nIn October 24, 2019, under Health Minister Shandro, Alberta's consolidated laboratory services previously provided by multiple organizations in Alberta under the newly named Alberta Precision Laboratories Ltd (APL), a wholly owned subsidiary of AHS, with Tammy Hofer as Chief Operating Officer (CFO) and Dr. Carolyn O\u2019Hara as Chief Medical Laboratory Officer (CMLO).<ref name=\"APL_201910\">{{Cite web|work = Alberta Precision Laboratories (APL)| title = Integrated lab medicine moves forward| access-date = April 4, 2020 |date=October 24, 2019| url = https://www.albertaprecisionlabs.ca/Page13747.aspx}}</ref> Prior to consolidation and during the transition period, laboratory services were provided to AHS through Calgary Lab Services (CLS), Covenant Health\u2014the largest Catholic health-care provider in Canada, DynaLIFE, Laboratory Services (AHS), Medicine Hat & Brooks Collection Sites, and Lamont Health Care Centre.<ref name=\"APL_About_20191024\">{{Cite web| title = About| work = Alberta Precision Laboratories|date=October 24, 2019| access-date = April 4, 2020| url = https://www.albertaprecisionlabs.ca/}}</ref>\n\nAs of October 2019, APL continued to \"work collaboratively with DynaLIFE, under contract to provide lab services in Alberta.\"<ref name=\"APL_About_20191024\"/>\n\nAHS testing services include AHS Lab Services (Central, Edmonton, North and South zones), Genetic Lab Services, ProvLab, Calgary Laboratory Services, and DynaLIFE Medical Labs.<ref name=\"APL_Directory_20191024\">{{Cite web| title = Directory| work = Alberta Precision Laboratories|date=October 24, 2019| access-date = April 4, 2020| url = https://www.albertaprecisionlabs.ca/}}</ref>\n\nProvLab, which \"operates under Alberta Health Services (AHS) Laboratory Services\" and has \"been in existence for over 100 years\", was renamed Public Health Laboratories. It is based in Calgary's [[Foothills Medical Centre]] and Edmonton's [[University of Alberta]] Hospital in Edmonton. Its focus on \"public health and specialized microbiology\" including \"surveillance, research, specialized laboratory testing and outbreak and emerging infectious diseases response.\"<ref>{{Cite web| title = Public Health Laboratories (ProvLab)| work = Alberta Health Services| access-date = April 4, 2020| url = https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/lab/page3317.aspx}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alberta]], [[Alberta Precision Laboratories]] (APL), a wholly-owned subsidiary of AHS, undertook testing for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web| last = Allison| first = Leanne| title = AHS to receive handheld COVID-19 testing devices| work = Discover Airdrie| accessdate = 2020-04-04| url = https://discoverairdrie.com/local/ahs-to-receive-handheld-covid-19-testing-devices}}</ref>\n\nClinical Support Services and CancerControl Alberta report directly to AHS President and CEO, Dr. Verna Yiu.<ref name=\"APL_201910\"/>\n\n===South Zone===\nThe south zone includes major centres such as Lethbridge and Medicine Hat serving approximately 300,000 Albertans.  \nA large network of hospitals is maintained in the outlying communities of Alberta. South Zone includes<ref name=\"albertahealthservices1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/facilities.asp?pid=ftype&type=3 |title=AHS hospital list |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201072351/http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/facilities.asp?pid=ftype&type=3 |archive-date=December 1, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSouth zone hospitals include Big Country Health Centre ([[Oyen]]), [[Bassano Health Centre]] ([[Bassano, Alberta|Bassano]]), Bow Island Health Centre ([[Bow Island]]), [[Brooks Health Centre]] ([[Brooks, Alberta|Brooks]]), Cardston Health Centre ([[Cardston]]), [[Chinook Regional Hospital]] ([[Lethbridge]]), Coaldale Health Centre ([[Coaldale, Alberta|Coaldale]]), Crowsnest Pass Health Centre ([[Blairmore, Alberta|Blairmore]]), Fort Macleod Health Centre ([[Fort Macleod]]), Medicine Hat Regional Hospital ([[Medicine Hat]]), [[Milk River Health Centre]] ([[Milk River, Alberta|Milk River]]), Piiyami Health Centre ([[Picture Butte]]), Pincher Creek Health Centre ([[Pincher Creek]]), Raymond Health Centre ([[Raymond, Alberta|Raymond]]), and Taber Health Centre ([[Taber, Alberta|Taber]]).\n\n===Calgary Zone===\nThe Calgary Zone administrative offices are located in the [[Southland Park]] business complex. Calgary Zone comprises territory formerly administered by the former [[Calgary Health Region]] and includes five major acute care sites (hospitals) including [[Foothills Medical Centre]], [[Peter Lougheed Centre]], [[Rockyview General Hospital]], [[South Health Campus]], and [[Alberta Children's Hospital]]. Serving approximately 1,400,000 Albertans.\n\nA large network of hospitals are maintained in the outlying communities of Alberta. Calgary Zone includes<ref name=\"albertahealthservices1\"/> [[Canmore General Hospital]] ([[Canmore, Alberta|Canmore]]), Claresholm General Hospital ([[Claresholm]]), Didsbury District Health Services ([[Didsbury, Alberta|Didsbury]]), High River General Hospital ([[High River]]), Strathmore District Health Services ([[Strathmore, Alberta|Strathmore]]), and Vulcan Community Health Centre ([[Vulcan, Alberta|Vulcan]]).\n\n===Central Zone===\nThe central zone includes major centres such as Red Deer.  Serving approximately 450,000 Albertans.\nA large network of hospitals are maintained in the outlying communities of Alberta. Central Zone includes<ref name=\"albertahealthservices1\"/>\n*Castor - Our Lady of the Rosary Hospital ([[Castor, Alberta|Castor]])\n*Consort Hospital and Care Centre ([[Consort, Alberta|Consort]])\n*Coronation Hospital and Care Centre ([[Coronation, Alberta|Coronation]])\n\n===Edmonton Zone===\nServing approximately 1.3 million Albertans, the Edmonton Zone administrative offices are located in Seventh Street Plaza. The Edmonton Zone comprises territory formerly administered by the [[Capital Health (Alberta)|Capital Health]] Region and includes eight acute care sites (hospitals) in the metropolitan area, which include.<ref name=\"albertahealthservices1\"/> \n* [[Alberta Hospital Edmonton]] ([[Edmonton]])\n* [[Devon General Hospital]] ([[Devon, Alberta|Devon]])\n* [[Fort Saskatchewan Community Hospital]] ([[Fort Saskatchewan]])\n* [[Glenrose Rehabilitation Hospital]] (Edmonton)\n* [[Grey Nuns Community Hospital]] (Edmonton)\n* [[Leduc Community Hospital]] ([[Leduc, Alberta|Leduc]]\n* [[Misericordia Community Hospital]] (Edmonton)\n* [[Royal Alexandra Hospital, Edmonton|Royal Alexandra Hospital]]  (Edmonton)\n* [[St. Joseph's Auxiliary Hospital]] (Edmonton)\n* [[Stollery Children's Hospital]] (Edmonton) \n* [[Strathcona Community Hospital]] ([[Sherwood Park]])\n* [[Sturgeon Community Hospital]] ([[St. Albert, Alberta|St. Albert]])\n* [[University of Alberta Hospital]] (Edmonton) \n* [[WestView Health Centre]] ([[Stony Plain, Alberta|Stony Plain]])\n\n===North Zone===\nThe north zone includes major centres such as Grande Prairie and Fort McMurray.  Serving approximately 450,000 Albertans.\nA large network of hospitals are maintained in the outlying communities of Alberta. North Zone includes<ref name=\"albertahealthservices1\"/>\n*Queen Elizabeth II (QEII) Hospital ([[Grande Prairie]])\n*[[Athabasca Healthcare Centre]] ([[Athabasca, Alberta|Athabasca]])\n*Barrhead Healthcare Centre ([[Barrhead, Alberta|Barrhead]])\n*Beaverlodge Municipal Hospital ([[Beaverlodge]])\n*Bonnyville Healthcare Centre ([[Bonnyville]])\n*Boyle Healthcare Centre ([[Boyle, Alberta|Boyle]])\n*Central Peace Health Complex ([[Spirit River, Alberta|Spirit River]])\n*Cold Lake Healthcare Centre ([[Cold Lake, Alberta|Cold Lake]])\n*St. Therese Healthcare Centre ([[St. Paul, Alberta|St. Paul]])\n\n===Rural Zone===\nA large network of hospitals are maintained in the outlying communities of Alberta. They include<ref name=\"albertahealthservices1\"/>\n\n*Crowsnest Pass Health Centre ([[Blairmore, Alberta|Blairmore]])\n*Daysland Health Centre ([[Daysland]])\n*[[Devon General Hospital]] ([[Devon, Alberta|Devon]])\n*Drayton Valley Hospital and Care Centre ([[Drayton Valley]])\n*Drumheller Health Centre ([[Drumheller]])\n*Edson Healthcare Centre ([[Edson, Alberta|Edson]])\n*Elk Point Healthcare Centre ([[Elk Point, Alberta|Elk Point]])\n*Fairview Health Complex ([[Fairview, Alberta|Fairview]])\n*Fort McMurray Northern Lights Regional Health Centre ([[Fort McMurray]])\n*[[Fort Saskatchewan Health Centre]] ([[Fort Saskatchewan]])\n*Fort Vermilion St. Theresa General Hospital ([[Fort Vermilion, Alberta|Fort Vermilion]])\n*Fox Creek Health Care Centre ([[Fox Creek, Alberta|Fox Creek]])\n*Grande Cache Community Health Complex ([[Grande Cache]])\n*Grimshaw/Berwyn Community Health Complex ([[Grimshaw, Alberta|Grimshaw]])\n*Hanna Health Centre ([[Hanna, Alberta|Hanna]])\n*Hardisty Health Centre ([[Hardisty]])\n*High Level Northwest Health Centre ([[High Level, Alberta|High Level]])\n*High Prairie Health Complex ([[High Prairie]])\n*[[Hinton Healthcare Centre]] ([[Hinton, Alberta|Hinton]])\n*Innisfail Health Centre ([[Innisfail, Alberta|Innisfail]])\n*Jasper - Seton Healthcare Centre ([[Jasper, Alberta|Jasper]])\n*Killam Health Care Centre ([[Killam, Alberta|Killam]])\n*Lac La Biche - William J. Cadzow Healthcare Centre ([[Lac La Biche, Alberta|Lac La Biche]])\n*Lacombe Hospital and Care Centre ([[Lacombe, Alberta|Lacombe]])\n*Lamont Health Care Centre ([[Lamont, Alberta|Lamont]])\n*[[Leduc Community Hospital]] ([[Leduc, Alberta|Leduc]])\n*Manning Community Health Centre ([[Manning, Alberta|Manning]])\n*Mayerthorpe Healthcare Centre ([[Mayerthorpe]])\n*[[Medicine Hat Regional Hospital]] ([[Medicine Hat]])\n*Oilfields General Hospital ([[Black Diamond, Alberta|Black Diamond]])\n*Olds Hospital and Care Centre ([[Olds, Alberta|Olds]])\n*Oyen - Big Country Hospital ([[Oyen]])\n*Peace River Community Health Centre ([[Peace River, Alberta|Peace River]])\n*Pincher Creek Health Centre ([[Pincher Creek]])\n*Ponoka Hospital and Care Centre ([[Ponoka, Alberta|Ponoka]])\n*Provost Health Centre ([[Provost, Alberta|Provost]])\n*Queen Elizabeth II Hospital ([[Grande Prairie]])\n*Raymond Health Centre ([[Raymond, Alberta|Raymond]])\n*[[Red Deer Regional Hospital]] ([[Red Deer, Alberta|Red Deer]])\n*[[Redwater Health Centre]] ([[Redwater, Alberta|Redwater]])\n*Rimbey Hospital and Care Centre ([[Rimbey]])\n*Rocky Mountain House Health Centre ([[Rocky Mountain House]])\n*Sacred Heart Community Health Centre ([[McLennan, Alberta|McLennan]])\n*Slave Lake Healthcare Centre ([[Slave Lake, Alberta|Slave Lake]])\n*Smoky Lake - George McDougall Healthcare Centre ([[Smoky Lake]])\n*St. Joseph's General Hospital ([[Vegreville]])\n*St. Mary's Hospital ([[Camrose, Alberta|Camrose]])\n*St. Paul - St. Therese Healthcare Centre ([[St. Paul, Alberta|St. Paul]])\n*Stettler Hospital and Care Centre ([[Stettler, Alberta|Stettler]])\n*Stony Plain - WestView Health Centre ([[Stony Plain, Alberta|Stony Plain]])\n*[[Sturgeon Community Hospital]] ([[St. Albert, Alberta|St. Albert]])\n*Sundre Hospital and Care Centre ([[Sundre]])\n*Swan Hills Healthcare Centre ([[Swan Hills]])\n*Sylvan Lake Community Health Centre ([[Sylvan Lake, Alberta|Sylvan Lake]])\n*Taber Health Centre ([[Taber, Alberta|Taber]])\n*Three Hills Health Centre ([[Three Hills]])\n*Tofield Health Centre ([[Tofield]])\n*Two Hills Health Centre ([[Two Hills, Alberta|Two Hills]])\n*Valleyview Health Centre ([[Valleyview, Alberta|Valleyview]])\n*Vermilion Health Centre ([[Vermilion, Alberta|Vermilion]])\n*Viking Health Centre ([[Viking, Alberta|Viking]])\n*Wabasca/Desmarais Healthcare Centre ([[Wabasca, Alberta|Wabasca]])\n*Wainwright Health Centre ([[Wainwright, Alberta|Wainwright]])\n*Westlock Healthcare Centre ([[Westlock]])\n*Wetaskiwin Hospital and Care Centre ([[Wetaskiwin]])\n*[[Whitecourt Healthcare Centre]] ([[Whitecourt]])\n\n==Emergency medical services==\n[[File:Alberta Health Services Tahoe.jpg|thumb|EMS [[Chevrolet Tahoe|Tahoe]]]]\nIn addition to providing acute care, Alberta Health Services took over responsibility for all emergency medical services (EMS) from municipalities on April 1, 2009, making ground ambulances a responsibility of the provincial government.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/209.asp |title=AHS backgrounder |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201224754/http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/209.asp |archive-date=December 1, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nProvincial air ambulance transitioned to AHS in April 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/209.asp |title=EMS Transition |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201224754/http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/209.asp |archive-date=December 1, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Also included in the provincial model of EMS are inter-facility hospital transfers, and EMS dispatch.\n\nIn 2013, EMS averaged about 370,000 ambulance responses annually,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.health.alberta.ca/services/EHS-ambulance-services.html |title=Ground and air ambulance services |publisher=Health.alberta.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107174956/http://www.health.alberta.ca/services/EHS-ambulance-services.html |archive-date=January 7, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> with approximately 30% of these being patient transfers between health care facilities, and 70% being emergency responses.\n\nEMS is provided through a hybrid of direct delivery and contracted services.  In 2013 this hybrid consisted of 204 ground ambulance locations. Practitioners include approximately 3,000 paramedics, emergency medical technicians and emergency medical responders.\n\nThere are 550 ambulances throughout the province, including 278 owned and operated by AHS.\n\nIn addition to land-based ambulances, AHS contracts 12 fixed-wing aircraft to provide 24-hour air ambulance services throughout the province. 5,500 patients were transferred by fixed-wing aircraft via contracted air ambulance providers in Alberta in 2010.\n\n==Comparison with other provinces==\nIn general, Alberta, which has been the province with the highest GDP for decades, spends more money on public services, including on health, than any other Canadian province.<ref name=\"EY_AHS_20191231\"/>{{rp|3}} According to a 2019 report, health care accounts for about 43% of the public expenditures in the province.<ref name=\"EY_AHS_20191231\"/>{{rp|3}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{ABGovDept}}\n\n[[Category:Health regions of Alberta]]\n[[Category:Alberta government departments and agencies]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Edmonton]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Alberta]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| name = Alberta Health Services\n| type = Health care\n| seal = \n| logo = File:Alberta Health Services Logo.svg\n| formed = {{Start date and age|2009|04|01}}\n| preceding1 = Aspen Health Region\n| preceding2 = Calgary Health Region\n| jurisdiction = [[Government of Alberta]]\n| headquarters = [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]]\n| motto = Healthy Albertans. Healthy Communities. Together.\n| employees = 109,000 (2017)<ref name=\"16-17\">{{cite web|title=Alberta Health Services 2016-17 Annual Report|url=https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/assets/about/publications/ahs-pub-2016-2017-annual-report.pdf|website=Alberta Health Services|publisher=Alberta Health Services|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107005418/https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/assets/about/publications/ahs-pub-2016-2017-annual-report.pdf|archivedate=January 6, 2018|language=English|accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n| budget = $21.4 billion (2017)<ref name=\"Budget\">{{cite web|title=Health funding forecast: 2017 Q2 Update|url=http://www.health.alberta.ca/about/health-funding.html|website=Health Alberta|publisher=Government of Alberta|accessdate=January 6, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107005335/http://www.health.alberta.ca/about/health-funding.html|archivedate=January 6, 2018|language=English|date=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n| minister1_name = [[Tyler Shandro]]\n| minister1_pfo = Minister of Health\n| minister2_name = \n| minister2_pfo = \n| deputyminister1_name = \n| deputyminister1_pfo = \n| deputyminister2_name = \n| deputyminister2_pfo = \n| chief1_name = \n| chief1_position = \n| chief2_name = \n| chief2_position = \n| chief3_name = \n| chief3_position = \n| chief4_name = \n| chief4_position = \n| chief5_name = \n| chief5_position = \n| chief6_name = \n| public_protector = \n| deputy = \n| chief6_position = \n| chief7_name = \n| chief7_position = \n| chief8_name = \n| chief8_position = \n| chief9_name = \n| chief9_position = \n| parent_department = [[Government of Alberta]]\n| parent_agency = Alberta Health<ref name=\"ABH\">{{cite web|title=Alberta Health|url=http://www.health.alberta.ca/|website=Health Alberta|publisher=Government of Alberta|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107005556/http://www.health.alberta.ca/|archivedate=January 6, 2018|language=English|accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|https://albertahealthservices.ca}}\n| agency_id = \n}}\n'''Alberta Health Services''' ('''AHS''') is the single [[Health regions of Canada|health authority]] for the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian province]] of [[Alberta]].\n\nAlberta Health Services delivers medical care on behalf of the [[Government of Alberta]]'s Ministry of Health<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.health.alberta.ca/|website=Alberta Health|title=Alberta Health|publisher=Government of Alberta|access-date=January 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107073622/http://www.health.alberta.ca/|archive-date=January 7, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> through 400 facilities throughout the province, including hospitals, clinics, continuing care facilities, mental health facilities and community health sites, while providing a variety of programs and services.\n\nAHS is the largest single health authority in Canada and is the largest employer in the province of Alberta as well as being the fifth largest single employer in Canada.\n\nAlberta Health Services is headquartered in [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]].\n\n==Overview==\nAccording to the December 31, 2019 [[Ernst & Young]] review of AHS performance commissioned by Alberta Health, Alberta has Canada's \"largest integrated provincial health care system\". AHS served 4.3 Albertan and had a staff of 125,000 staff and 10,000 physicians.<ref name=\"EY_AHS_20191231\">{{Cite report| title = Alberta Health Services Performance Review Summary Report |date=December 31, 2019| access-date = April 5, 2020| url = https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/c0724ccd-832e-41bc-90d6-a0cd16bc6954/resource/1e03ea8a-7948-48c4-bca4-109c20ce0f02/download/health-ahs-review-summary-report.pdf |format=PDF |work=[[Ernst & Young]] |pages=101}}</ref>{{rp|3}} Ernst & Young said that AHS was \"one of Canada's top 100 employers.\" AHS foundations raise over $250 million annually.<ref name=\"EY_AHS_20191231\"/>{{rp|3}}\n\n==History==\nThe Alberta Health Services, which was established in May 15, 2008, as a quasi-independent agency of the Alberta government to public health services throughout the province. \n\n[[Ed Stelmach]], who served as Alberta's premier from December 2006 to October 2011, as leader of the [[Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta]], introduced major reforms to Alberta's health-care system. On May 15, 2008, Health Minister [[Ron Liepert]] announced that as of April 1, 2009, one provincial governance board\u2014the Alberta Health Services Board\u2014would consolidate the \"$13-billion-a-year system into one public corporation\", replacing Alberta's nine regional health authority boards\u2014 Aspen Health Region, Calgary Health Region, Capital Health Region, Chinook Health Region, David Thompson Health Region, East Central Health Region, Northern Lights Health Region, Palliser Health Region, and Peace Country Health Region.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Markusoff_20080515\">{{cite news|url=http://www.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/story.html?id=4b0743f0-2046-4b13-8be7-7e2e4ca7e10d |title=Tories create health superboard: Stelmach plan will see single body rule nine regions |first1=Jason |last1=Markusoff |first2=Archie |last2=McLean |access-date=June 12, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090509222347/http://www2.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/story.html?id=4b0743f0-2046-4b13-8be7-7e2e4ca7e10d |archivedate=May 9, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2009, the Health Governance Transition Amendment Act dissolved the Alberta Mental Health Board, the Alberta Cancer Board and the Alberta Alcohol and Drug Abuse Commission,<ref name=\"Liepert_2009\">{{cite report |last=Liepert |first=RON |date=2009 |title=Provincial health structure: Alberta |series=Health Innovation Report|url=http://www.healthinnovationforum.org/2009/nov/01/recent-changes-health-structures-alberta/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124083008/http://www.healthinnovationforum.org/2009/nov/01/recent-changes-health-structures-alberta/ |archivedate=January 24, 2010 |access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|12\u20133}}<ref>{{citation |last=Philippon |first= D. |date=2009 |title=Health care system reorganization: expectations, approaches and impact |series=Health Innovation Report}}</ref>{{rp|44\u201349}} and completed the transition to Alberta Health Services (AHS).<ref name=\"AHS_history_2018\">{{cite web|title=Who We Are |url=https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/about/about.aspx|website=Alberta Health Services|publisher=Alberta Health Services|accessdate=January 6, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107010616/https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/about/about.aspx|archivedate=January 6, 2018|language=English}}</ref>\n\nPrior to these changes, health services in Alberta had undergone several governance reorganization which had resulted in fewer separate public organizational entities, in 1996,<ref>Philippon, D. J. and S. A. Wasylyshyn (1996). Health-care reform in Alberta. ''Canadian Public Administration'' 39(1): 70-84.</ref><ref>Reay, T. and C. R. Hinings (2005). The Recomposition of an Organizational Field: Health Care in Alberta. ''Organization Studies'' 26(3): 351-384.</ref> 2003,<ref>Hinings, C. R., A. Casebeer, et al. (2003). Regionalizing Healthcare in Alberta: Legislated Change, Uncertainty and Loose Coupling ''[[British Journal of Management]]'' 14:S1(December): S15-S30.</ref> and 2006.<ref>Casebeer, A., T. Reay, et al. (2006). Experiences of Regionalization: Assessing Multiple Stakeholder Perspectives across Time. ''Healthcare Quarterly'' 9(2): 32-43.</ref>\n\n==Mission and organization==\nAHS provides health services to some patients in British Columbia, Saskatchewan, and the Northwest Territories, as well as to over 4.3 million Albertans.<ref name=\"EY_AHS_20191231\"/>{{rp|3}} \n\nAlberta Health Services has articulated three broad goals (access, quality and sustainability) which expand into eight 'areas of focus' (e.g. improving access, fit for the future, learning and improving) and 20 strategic priorities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/files/org-strategic-direction.pdf |title=strategic direction |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |date= |accessdate=January 7, 2018 }}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAlberta Health Services has been organized so as to separate acute hospital facilities (with separate reporting lines for major tertiary, metropolitan and regional hospitals) from smaller hospitals and community services, the latter of which are organized into five zones (North, Edmonton, Central, Calgary and South).  The Calgary Zone, for example, includes some sites and services formerly administered by the [[Calgary Health Region]] while other services have been reorganized on a provincial scale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/files/org-orgchart.pdf |title=formal structure |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007191554/http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/files/org-orgchart.pdf |archive-date=October 7, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nThe organization was initially overseen by a board of directors, followed by an official administrator, and most recently, again by a board of directors. The Alberta Health Services Board reports to the Minister of Health.<ref name=\"EY_AHS_20191231\"/>{{rp|3}} \n\n[[Stephen Duckett]] was the inaugural president and chief executive officer of the newly created health \"superboard\", Alberta Health Services, and served from the spring of 2009 until November 2010, when then-provincial Health Minister [[Gene Zwozdesky]] asked him to resign.<ref name=\"CBC_20201224\">{{Cite news| date = November 24, 2010| title = Alberta health board replaces controversial CEO|work= CBC News| access-date = April 5, 2020| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-health-board-replaces-controversial-ceo-1.886067}}</ref> Significant budget cuts\u2014of about CA $1 billion\u2014were imposed on AHS by Premier Stelmach, soon after Duckett's appointment.<ref name=\"CBC_20090828\">{{Cite news| date = August 28, 2009| title = Health-care buyouts spark interest, raise concerns |work=CBC News| access-date = April 5, 2020| date = 2009-08-28| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/health-care-buyouts-spark-interest-raise-concerns-1.826258}}</ref> \n\nChris Eagle served as AHS CEO from November 23, 2010 until October 17, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/9226.asp |title=\"Dr. Chris Eagle steps down as AHS CEO\" |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031222854/http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/9226.asp |archive-date=October 31, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  \n\nOn June 12, 2013, Minister of Health [[Fred Horne]] fired the entire AHS Board over its refusal to cancel executive bonuses.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/alberta-health-minister-fires-board-over-executive-bonuses/article12490983/ |title=\"Alberta Health Minister fires entire board over executive bonuses\" |access-date=August 23, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814214121/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/alberta-health-minister-fires-board-over-executive-bonuses/article12490983/ |archive-date=August 14, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Three days later, Janet Davidson<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.health.alberta.ca/documents/NewBG-2013-06-15-AHS-Admin.pdf |title=\"Appointment details, AHS Administrator Janet M. Davidson\" |access-date=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011214023/http://www.health.alberta.ca/documents/NewBG-2013-06-15-AHS-Admin.pdf |archive-date=October 11, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> was appointed the AHS official administrator by Minister Horne to act in place of its board of directors. On September 12, 2013, John W. F. Cowell replaced Davidson as the official administrator.<ref>{{cite web |author=Government of Alberta |url=http://alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=34957BA1F0D67-C2F5-6A9F-C3AA752F708F46D0 |title=\"Statement from Health Minister Fred Horne on the appointment of Dr. Cowell\" |publisher=Alberta.ca |date=September 12, 2013 |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104223119/http://alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=34957BA1F0D67-C2F5-6A9F-C3AA752F708F46D0 |archive-date=January 4, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> AHS has subsequently had Carl Amrhein and David Carpenter as official administrators.\n\nVickie Kaminski served from May 2014 until her<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/vickie-kaminski-resigns-as-ceo-of-alberta-health-services-1.3340201 |title=\"Vickie Kaminski resigns as CEO of Alberta Health Services\" |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=November 27, 2015 |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008041325/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/vickie-kaminski-resigns-as-ceo-of-alberta-health-services-1.3340201 |archive-date=October 8, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> resignation in late 2015. \n\nThe Alberta Health Services Board has been re-introduced, effective November 27, 2015 with Linda Hughes appointed as the board chair.<ref>{{cite web |author=Government of Alberta |url=https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=38722D3908842-FE39-E61E-98C591CBE1D023C4 |title=\"New Alberta Health Services Board features strong health care expertise\" |publisher=Alberta.ca |date=October 23, 2015 |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107174935/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=38722D3908842-FE39-E61E-98C591CBE1D023C4 |archive-date=January 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn June 3, 2016, Verna Yiu became CEO.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/about/Page11898.aspx |title=AHS Executive Leadership Team &#124; Dr. Verna Yiu |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |date=June 3, 2016 |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108120446/https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/about/Page11898.aspx |archive-date=January 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, [[David Weyant]], QC served as Board Chair, [[Brenda Hemmelgarn]] as Vice-Chair, and [[Brian Vaasjo]], [[David Carpenter]], [[Glenda Yeates]], [[Heidi Overguard]], [[Hugh D. Sommerville]], [[Richard Dicerni]], and [[Stephen Mandel]], serve as board members.<ref name=\"AHS_2020\">{{Cite web| title = Board Members| work = Alberta Health Services|date=2020| access-date = April 5, 2020| url = https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/about/Page12891.aspx}}</ref>\n\n==Employees==\nBy 2018, Alberta Health Services employs over 108,000 staff and more than 7,700 physicians,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/about/about.aspx |title=About AHS &#124; Alberta Health Services |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107010616/https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/about/about.aspx |archive-date=January 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> including clinical, administrative and support personnel across the province. Staff belong to a variety of professional organizations and associations, including [[United Nurses of Alberta]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.una.ab.ca/about |title=UNA \"about\" page |publisher=Una.ab.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108062413/https://www.una.ab.ca/about |archive-date=January 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> several locals of the [[Alberta Union of Provincial Employees]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aupe.org/about/ |title=AUPE \"about\" web page |publisher=Aupe.org |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108063342/https://www.aupe.org/about/ |archive-date=January 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the Health Sciences Association of Alberta.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hsaa.ca/about-HSAA |title=HSAA \"about\" page |access-date=January 4, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104204344/http://www.hsaa.ca/about-HSAA |archive-date=January 4, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n{{main|List of hospitals in Alberta}}\nBy 2010, AHS was maintaining and running a number of different types of facilities and services.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/facilities.asp |title=AHS facilities website |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201024752/http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/facilities.asp |archive-date=December 1, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> These included Cancer care for the prevention, detection, treatment, education and care of cancer patients, as well as to facilitate research of cancer; continuing and long-term care\nfor the treatment of patients with complex health needs requiring 24-hour on-site services from [[registered nurse]]s; emergency for immediate care of patients with all types of conditions; [[List of hospitals in Alberta|hospitals]] for medical, surgical, or psychiatric care of the sick and injured. There were also laboratories for the processing of medical samples and tests; mental health and addictions services for treatment and care of patients diagnosed with mental health or addiction issues and emergency medical services.\n\nAHS is directly responsible for both ground and air ambulance operations in the province, provided through a mix of both direct delivery and contracted providers.\n\nA wider array of miscellaneous health facilities include physiotherapy, occupational therapy, home care, hemodialysis and others, and also include Public Health Centres which provide services such as prenatal, postpartum, health promotion/disease and injury prevention, bereavement services, communicable disease and school health.  They also fund [[affordable housing]] for seniors at facilities, such as Silvera for Seniors.\n\nUrgent care services include treating patients with unexpected but not life-threatening issues requiring same day treatment.\n\nAHS also operates X-ray and imaging clinics for procedures such as [[MRI]]s, X-rays and other types of scans.\n\n===Laboratories===\n\nIn the early 1990s, most of Edmonton's hospital labs were privatized.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_20161004\">{{Cite web| title = Editorial: Alberta Health Services takeover of private lab services looks logical| work = Edmonton Journal|date=October 4, 2016| access-date = April 5, 2020| url = https://edmontonjournal.com/opinion/editorials/editorial-lab-transfer-looks-logical}}</ref>  The Edmonton regional health authority had a 15-year contract with the private company Dynalife, which was ending in the early 2010s.\n\nThe provincial government ordered regional health authorities to cut lab spending, which resulted in more public laboratories being established by 2005.\n\nBy 2006, all of the lab services in Calgary were under public control.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_20161004\"/>\n\nIn December 2013, Alberta Health Services proceeded with \"its plan to privatize all of its diagnostic lab services in Edmonton\".<ref name=\"CBC_20131211\">{{Cite news| date = December 11, 2013| title = Alberta Health Services privatizing Edmonton labs | work = CBC| access-date = April 4, 2020| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-health-services-privatizing-edmonton-labs-1.2460544}}</ref> AHS sent out request for proposals (RFP) for a \"private provider to establish a single $3 billion lab for the Edmonton Zone.\"<ref name=\"NCBI_Wright_20180726\">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1177/2374289518785373| issn = 2374-2895| volume = 5| last = Wright| first = James R.| title = When Pathology and Laboratory Medicine Becomes a Commodity and Health Care Becomes Both Its Customer and Owner| journal = Academic Pathology| access-date = April 5, 2020| date = July 26, 2018| url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6073830/| pmid = 30083594| pmc = 6073830}}</ref>{{rp|2}}<ref name=\"CBC_20131211\"/> By October 16, 2014, Australia's Sonic Healthcare, a private company, had been selected.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Australia's Sonic Healthcare nets $3B contract for Edmonton labs |work= CBC News|date=October 16, 2014| accessdate = 2020-04-05| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/australia-s-sonichealthcare-nets-3b-contract-for-edmonton-labs-1.2802270}}</ref> They would have replaced \"hospital labs operated by AHS and Covenant Health, as well as the services now provided by the private company Dynalife.\" When the NDP won the [[2015 Alberta general election]], the contract with Sonic was cancelled.\n\nBy 2016, the largest medical testing facility in northern Alberta was the a central laboratory facility owned and operated by a private company in Edmonton, Dynalife.<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Gerein_20200404\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta Health Services to take over Dynalife labs in 2022| work = Edmonton Journal|first=Keith |last=Gerein |date=October 1, 2016  | access-date = April 4, 2020| url = https://edmontonjournal.com/news/local-news/alberta-health-services-to-take-over-dynalife-labs-in-2022}}</ref> As of January 23, 2016, DynaLIFE Dx was owned by Toronto-headquartered LifeLabs and the [[Burlington, North Carolina]]-headquartered [[LabCorp]], or Laboratory Corporation of America Holdings, which operates one of the largest clinical laboratory networks in the world. LabCorp had acquired all outstanding shares of Canadian medical laboratory services company [[Dynacare|Dynacare Inc.]] for $480 million in May 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/dynacare-accepts-offer-from-labcorp/article1023077/|title=Dynacare accepts offer from LabCorp|last=|first=|date=2002-05-10|website=[[The Globe and Mail]]|publisher=Phillip Crawley|access-date=2016-10-14}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, Elisabeth Ballermann, then-President of the [[Health Sciences Association of Alberta]] (HSAA), which represented 1,600 lab workers in both the private and public sector, said that HSAA members had \"long wanted lab services delivered by the public system\". Ballerman said she was convinced, they could \"do high quality, world-class work in the public sector. She expressed concern\"that under the contract, the new facility to house the Edmonton lab would be owned by a private company, not by Albertans.\"<ref name=\"CBC_20150813\">{{Cite news| title = Health minister cancels $3B lab contract with Sonic Healthcare |work=CBC News| work = CBC| access-date = April 4, 2020| date = August 13, 2015| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/health-minister-cancels-3b-contract-will-not-expand-private-services-in-alberta-1.3190004}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, then-Premier [[Rachel Notley]], leader of the [[Alberta New Democratic Party]], announced that the [[Alberta New Democratic Party]] (NDP) government was beginning the process of taking over testing done by Dynacare as part of the NDP's campaign promises during the [[2015 Alberta general election]], to \"bring medical lab services under greater public control.\"<ref name=\"edmontonjournal_Gerein_20200404\"/>\n\nThe newly-elected [[United Conservative Party]] (UCP) government's Health Minister [[Tyler Shandro]], cancelled the construction of a new super-lab\u2014a \"$595-million centralized public lab facility next to the University of Alberta\u2019s south campus\".<ref name=\"canhealth_20190626\">{{Cite web| title = Alberta's new government cancels superlab |work= Canadian Healthcare Technology| access-date = April 4, 2020 |date=June 26, 2019| url = https://www.canhealth.com/2019/06/26/albertas-new-government-cancels-superlab/}}</ref>  Shandro also exited the \"planned $50-million buyout of private lab services company Dynalife by 2022\", saying that he disagreed with the NDP's decision to \"nationalize Dynalife \u2013 to nationalize laboratory services in Alberta.\u201d<ref name=\"canhealth_20190626\"/>\n\nIn October 24, 2019, under Health Minister Shandro, Alberta's consolidated laboratory services previously provided by multiple organizations in Alberta under the newly named Alberta Precision Laboratories Ltd (APL), a wholly owned subsidiary of AHS, with Tammy Hofer as Chief Operating Officer (CFO) and Dr. Carolyn O\u2019Hara as Chief Medical Laboratory Officer (CMLO).<ref name=\"APL_201910\">{{Cite web|work = Alberta Precision Laboratories (APL)| title = Integrated lab medicine moves forward| access-date = April 4, 2020 |date=October 24, 2019| url = https://www.albertaprecisionlabs.ca/Page13747.aspx}}</ref> Prior to consolidation and during the transition period, laboratory services were provided to AHS through Calgary Lab Services (CLS), Covenant Health\u2014the largest Catholic health-care provider in Canada, DynaLIFE, Laboratory Services (AHS), Medicine Hat & Brooks Collection Sites, and Lamont Health Care Centre.<ref name=\"APL_About_20191024\">{{Cite web| title = About| work = Alberta Precision Laboratories|date=October 24, 2019| access-date = April 4, 2020| url = https://www.albertaprecisionlabs.ca/}}</ref>\n\nAs of October 2019, APL continued to \"work collaboratively with DynaLIFE, under contract to provide lab services in Alberta.\"<ref name=\"APL_About_20191024\"/>\n\nAHS testing services include AHS Lab Services (Central, Edmonton, North and South zones), Genetic Lab Services, ProvLab, Calgary Laboratory Services, and DynaLIFE Medical Labs.<ref name=\"APL_Directory_20191024\">{{Cite web| title = Directory| work = Alberta Precision Laboratories|date=October 24, 2019| access-date = April 4, 2020| url = https://www.albertaprecisionlabs.ca/}}</ref>\n\nProvLab, which \"operates under Alberta Health Services (AHS) Laboratory Services\" and has \"been in existence for over 100 years\", was renamed Public Health Laboratories. It is based in Calgary's [[Foothills Medical Centre]] and Edmonton's [[University of Alberta]] Hospital in Edmonton. Its focus on \"public health and specialized microbiology\" including \"surveillance, research, specialized laboratory testing and outbreak and emerging infectious diseases response.\"<ref>{{Cite web| title = Public Health Laboratories (ProvLab)| work = Alberta Health Services| access-date = April 4, 2020| url = https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/lab/page3317.aspx}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alberta]], [[Alberta Precision Laboratories]] (APL), a wholly-owned subsidiary of AHS, undertook testing for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web| last = Allison| first = Leanne| title = AHS to receive handheld COVID-19 testing devices| work = Discover Airdrie| accessdate = 2020-04-04| url = https://discoverairdrie.com/local/ahs-to-receive-handheld-covid-19-testing-devices}}</ref>\n\nClinical Support Services and CancerControl Alberta report directly to AHS President and CEO, Dr. Verna Yiu.<ref name=\"APL_201910\"/>\n\n===South Zone===\nThe south zone includes major centres such as Lethbridge and Medicine Hat serving approximately 300,000 Albertans.  \nA large network of hospitals is maintained in the outlying communities of Alberta. South Zone includes<ref name=\"albertahealthservices1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/facilities.asp?pid=ftype&type=3 |title=AHS hospital list |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201072351/http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/facilities.asp?pid=ftype&type=3 |archive-date=December 1, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSouth zone hospitals include Big Country Health Centre ([[Oyen]]), [[Bassano Health Centre]] ([[Bassano, Alberta|Bassano]]), Bow Island Health Centre ([[Bow Island]]), [[Brooks Health Centre]] ([[Brooks, Alberta|Brooks]]), Cardston Health Centre ([[Cardston]]), [[Chinook Regional Hospital]] ([[Lethbridge]]), Coaldale Health Centre ([[Coaldale, Alberta|Coaldale]]), Crowsnest Pass Health Centre ([[Blairmore, Alberta|Blairmore]]), Fort Macleod Health Centre ([[Fort Macleod]]), Medicine Hat Regional Hospital ([[Medicine Hat]]), [[Milk River Health Centre]] ([[Milk River, Alberta|Milk River]]), Piiyami Health Centre ([[Picture Butte]]), Pincher Creek Health Centre ([[Pincher Creek]]), Raymond Health Centre ([[Raymond, Alberta|Raymond]]), and Taber Health Centre ([[Taber, Alberta|Taber]]).\n\n===Calgary Zone===\nThe Calgary Zone administrative offices are located in the [[Southland Park]] business complex. Calgary Zone comprises territory formerly administered by the former [[Calgary Health Region]] and includes five major acute care sites (hospitals) including [[Foothills Medical Centre]], [[Peter Lougheed Centre]], [[Rockyview General Hospital]], [[South Health Campus]], and [[Alberta Children's Hospital]]. Serving approximately 1,400,000 Albertans.\n\nA large network of hospitals are maintained in the outlying communities of Alberta. Calgary Zone includes<ref name=\"albertahealthservices1\"/> [[Canmore General Hospital]] ([[Canmore, Alberta|Canmore]]), Claresholm General Hospital ([[Claresholm]]), Didsbury District Health Services ([[Didsbury, Alberta|Didsbury]]), High River General Hospital ([[High River]]), Strathmore District Health Services ([[Strathmore, Alberta|Strathmore]]), and Vulcan Community Health Centre ([[Vulcan, Alberta|Vulcan]]).\n\n===Central Zone===\nThe central zone includes major centres such as Red Deer.  Serving approximately 450,000 Albertans.\nA large network of hospitals are maintained in the outlying communities of Alberta. Central Zone includes<ref name=\"albertahealthservices1\"/>\n*Castor - Our Lady of the Rosary Hospital ([[Castor, Alberta|Castor]])\n*Consort Hospital and Care Centre ([[Consort, Alberta|Consort]])\n*Coronation Hospital and Care Centre ([[Coronation, Alberta|Coronation]])\n\n===Edmonton Zone===\nServing approximately 1.3 million Albertans, the Edmonton Zone administrative offices are located in Seventh Street Plaza. The Edmonton Zone comprises territory formerly administered by the [[Capital Health (Alberta)|Capital Health]] Region and includes eight acute care sites (hospitals) in the metropolitan area, which include.<ref name=\"albertahealthservices1\"/> \n* [[Alberta Hospital Edmonton]] ([[Edmonton]])\n* [[Devon General Hospital]] ([[Devon, Alberta|Devon]])\n* [[Fort Saskatchewan Community Hospital]] ([[Fort Saskatchewan]])\n* [[Glenrose Rehabilitation Hospital]] (Edmonton)\n* [[Grey Nuns Community Hospital]] (Edmonton)\n* [[Leduc Community Hospital]] ([[Leduc, Alberta|Leduc]]\n* [[Misericordia Community Hospital]] (Edmonton)\n* [[Royal Alexandra Hospital, Edmonton|Royal Alexandra Hospital]]  (Edmonton)\n* [[St. Joseph's Auxiliary Hospital]] (Edmonton)\n* [[Stollery Children's Hospital]] (Edmonton) \n* [[Strathcona Community Hospital]] ([[Sherwood Park]])\n* [[Sturgeon Community Hospital]] ([[St. Albert, Alberta|St. Albert]])\n* [[University of Alberta Hospital]] (Edmonton) \n* [[WestView Health Centre]] ([[Stony Plain, Alberta|Stony Plain]])\n\n===North Zone===\nThe north zone includes major centres such as Grande Prairie and Fort McMurray.  Serving approximately 450,000 Albertans.\nA large network of hospitals are maintained in the outlying communities of Alberta. North Zone includes<ref name=\"albertahealthservices1\"/>\n*Queen Elizabeth II (QEII) Hospital ([[Grande Prairie]])\n*[[Athabasca Healthcare Centre]] ([[Athabasca, Alberta|Athabasca]])\n*Barrhead Healthcare Centre ([[Barrhead, Alberta|Barrhead]])\n*Beaverlodge Municipal Hospital ([[Beaverlodge]])\n*Bonnyville Healthcare Centre ([[Bonnyville]])\n*Boyle Healthcare Centre ([[Boyle, Alberta|Boyle]])\n*Central Peace Health Complex ([[Spirit River, Alberta|Spirit River]])\n*Cold Lake Healthcare Centre ([[Cold Lake, Alberta|Cold Lake]])\n*St. Therese Healthcare Centre ([[St. Paul, Alberta|St. Paul]])\n\n===Rural Zone===\nA large network of hospitals are maintained in the outlying communities of Alberta. They include<ref name=\"albertahealthservices1\"/>\n\n*Crowsnest Pass Health Centre ([[Blairmore, Alberta|Blairmore]])\n*Daysland Health Centre ([[Daysland]])\n*[[Devon General Hospital]] ([[Devon, Alberta|Devon]])\n*Drayton Valley Hospital and Care Centre ([[Drayton Valley]])\n*Drumheller Health Centre ([[Drumheller]])\n*Edson Healthcare Centre ([[Edson, Alberta|Edson]])\n*Elk Point Healthcare Centre ([[Elk Point, Alberta|Elk Point]])\n*Fairview Health Complex ([[Fairview, Alberta|Fairview]])\n*Fort McMurray Northern Lights Regional Health Centre ([[Fort McMurray]])\n*[[Fort Saskatchewan Health Centre]] ([[Fort Saskatchewan]])\n*Fort Vermilion St. Theresa General Hospital ([[Fort Vermilion, Alberta|Fort Vermilion]])\n*Fox Creek Health Care Centre ([[Fox Creek, Alberta|Fox Creek]])\n*Grande Cache Community Health Complex ([[Grande Cache]])\n*Grimshaw/Berwyn Community Health Complex ([[Grimshaw, Alberta|Grimshaw]])\n*Hanna Health Centre ([[Hanna, Alberta|Hanna]])\n*Hardisty Health Centre ([[Hardisty]])\n*High Level Northwest Health Centre ([[High Level, Alberta|High Level]])\n*High Prairie Health Complex ([[High Prairie]])\n*[[Hinton Healthcare Centre]] ([[Hinton, Alberta|Hinton]])\n*Innisfail Health Centre ([[Innisfail, Alberta|Innisfail]])\n*Jasper - Seton Healthcare Centre ([[Jasper, Alberta|Jasper]])\n*Killam Health Care Centre ([[Killam, Alberta|Killam]])\n*Lac La Biche - William J. Cadzow Healthcare Centre ([[Lac La Biche, Alberta|Lac La Biche]])\n*Lacombe Hospital and Care Centre ([[Lacombe, Alberta|Lacombe]])\n*Lamont Health Care Centre ([[Lamont, Alberta|Lamont]])\n*[[Leduc Community Hospital]] ([[Leduc, Alberta|Leduc]])\n*Manning Community Health Centre ([[Manning, Alberta|Manning]])\n*Mayerthorpe Healthcare Centre ([[Mayerthorpe]])\n*[[Medicine Hat Regional Hospital]] ([[Medicine Hat]])\n*Oilfields General Hospital ([[Black Diamond, Alberta|Black Diamond]])\n*Olds Hospital and Care Centre ([[Olds, Alberta|Olds]])\n*Oyen - Big Country Hospital ([[Oyen]])\n*Peace River Community Health Centre ([[Peace River, Alberta|Peace River]])\n*Pincher Creek Health Centre ([[Pincher Creek]])\n*Ponoka Hospital and Care Centre ([[Ponoka, Alberta|Ponoka]])\n*Provost Health Centre ([[Provost, Alberta|Provost]])\n*Queen Elizabeth II Hospital ([[Grande Prairie]])\n*Raymond Health Centre ([[Raymond, Alberta|Raymond]])\n*[[Red Deer Regional Hospital]] ([[Red Deer, Alberta|Red Deer]])\n*[[Redwater Health Centre]] ([[Redwater, Alberta|Redwater]])\n*Rimbey Hospital and Care Centre ([[Rimbey]])\n*Rocky Mountain House Health Centre ([[Rocky Mountain House]])\n*Sacred Heart Community Health Centre ([[McLennan, Alberta|McLennan]])\n*Slave Lake Healthcare Centre ([[Slave Lake, Alberta|Slave Lake]])\n*Smoky Lake - George McDougall Healthcare Centre ([[Smoky Lake]])\n*St. Joseph's General Hospital ([[Vegreville]])\n*St. Mary's Hospital ([[Camrose, Alberta|Camrose]])\n*St. Paul - St. Therese Healthcare Centre ([[St. Paul, Alberta|St. Paul]])\n*Stettler Hospital and Care Centre ([[Stettler, Alberta|Stettler]])\n*Stony Plain - WestView Health Centre ([[Stony Plain, Alberta|Stony Plain]])\n*[[Sturgeon Community Hospital]] ([[St. Albert, Alberta|St. Albert]])\n*Sundre Hospital and Care Centre ([[Sundre]])\n*Swan Hills Healthcare Centre ([[Swan Hills]])\n*Sylvan Lake Community Health Centre ([[Sylvan Lake, Alberta|Sylvan Lake]])\n*Taber Health Centre ([[Taber, Alberta|Taber]])\n*Three Hills Health Centre ([[Three Hills]])\n*Tofield Health Centre ([[Tofield]])\n*Two Hills Health Centre ([[Two Hills, Alberta|Two Hills]])\n*Valleyview Health Centre ([[Valleyview, Alberta|Valleyview]])\n*Vermilion Health Centre ([[Vermilion, Alberta|Vermilion]])\n*Viking Health Centre ([[Viking, Alberta|Viking]])\n*Wabasca/Desmarais Healthcare Centre ([[Wabasca, Alberta|Wabasca]])\n*Wainwright Health Centre ([[Wainwright, Alberta|Wainwright]])\n*Westlock Healthcare Centre ([[Westlock]])\n*Wetaskiwin Hospital and Care Centre ([[Wetaskiwin]])\n*[[Whitecourt Healthcare Centre]] ([[Whitecourt]])\n\n==Emergency medical services==\n[[File:Alberta Health Services Tahoe.jpg|thumb|EMS [[Chevrolet Tahoe|Tahoe]]]]\nIn addition to providing acute care, Alberta Health Services took over responsibility for all emergency medical services (EMS) from municipalities on April 1, 2009, making ground ambulances a responsibility of the provincial government.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/209.asp |title=AHS backgrounder |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201224754/http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/209.asp |archive-date=December 1, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nProvincial air ambulance transitioned to AHS in April 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/209.asp |title=EMS Transition |publisher=Albertahealthservices.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201224754/http://www.albertahealthservices.ca/209.asp |archive-date=December 1, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Also included in the provincial model of EMS are inter-facility hospital transfers, and EMS dispatch.\n\nIn 2013, EMS averaged about 370,000 ambulance responses annually,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.health.alberta.ca/services/EHS-ambulance-services.html |title=Ground and air ambulance services |publisher=Health.alberta.ca |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107174956/http://www.health.alberta.ca/services/EHS-ambulance-services.html |archive-date=January 7, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> with approximately 30% of these being patient transfers between health care facilities, and 70% being emergency responses.\n\nEMS is provided through a hybrid of direct delivery and contracted services.  In 2013 this hybrid consisted of 204 ground ambulance locations. Practitioners include approximately 3,000 paramedics, emergency medical technicians and emergency medical responders.\n\nThere are 550 ambulances throughout the province, including 278 owned and operated by AHS.\n\nIn addition to land-based ambulances, AHS contracts 12 fixed-wing aircraft to provide 24-hour air ambulance services throughout the province. 5,500 patients were transferred by fixed-wing aircraft via contracted air ambulance providers in Alberta in 2010.\n\n==Comparison with other provinces==\nIn general, Alberta, which has been the province with the highest GDP for decades, spends more money on public services, including on health, than any other Canadian province.<ref name=\"EY_AHS_20191231\"/>{{rp|3}} According to a 2019 report, health care accounts for about 43% of the public expenditures in the province.<ref name=\"EY_AHS_20191231\"/>{{rp|3}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{ABGovDept}}\n\n[[Category:Health regions of Alberta]]\n[[Category:Alberta government departments and agencies]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Edmonton]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Alberta]]\n", "name_user": "Oceanflynn", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGovernance:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alberta_Health_Services"}
